ce:section.ce:para:
XRD analysis identified the crystal structure of ZnO, N-GQDs, and ZnO@N-GQDs@MIP (
                           Fig. S3
                        ). The XRD patterns of ZnO showed diffraction peaks at 32.1°, 34.8°, 36.1°, 48.0°, 56.9°, 63.2°, and 68.5°, demonstrating the successful preparation of high-crystalline ZnO. Meanwhile, N-GQDs showed a broad peak around 20-30°, corresponding to the amorphous graphitic carbon structure. The diffraction peaks of ZnO and N-GQDs were observed in the polymer curves, which confirmed the successful formation of ZnO@N-GQDs@MIP.

The chemical composition of ZnO@N-GQDs@MIP was determined by energy-dispersive x-ray spectroscopy (EDS). The corresponding elemental mapping images (
                           Fig. S4
                        ) confirmed the presence of characteristic elements (C, N, O, Si and Zn) within the ZnO@N-GQDs@MIP. The presence of C and N were attributed to the N-GQDs. The O elements were correlated with the Zn mapping, showing the presence of ZnO and contributions from N-GQDs. The Si mapping was attributed to the polymer of ZnO@N-GQDs@MIP. This evidence supports the successful fabrication of the ZnO@N-GQDs@MIP nanoprobe.

The effect of template molecule removal was investigated by considering the fluorescence intensity of a ZnO@N-GQDs@MIP probe before and after template removal and the fluorescence intensity of a ZnO@N-GQDs@NIP probe (
                           Fig. S5
                        ). Before template removal, the intensity of the fluorescence emission of the ZnO@N-GQDs@MIP probe (curve a) was low since only non-specific binding occurred between the probe and diflunisal (the template molecule). After template removal (curve b), fluorescence intensity was restored almost to the same level as the fluorescence intensity of the ZnO@N-GQDs@NIP probe (curve c). These results indicated the effect of template removal that enabled the determination of diflunisal in real samples.

The quenching of the probe by diflunisal could be explained by dynamic quenching since there was no overlap in the absorption spectrum of diflunisal (green dot line) and the fluorescence emission spectrum of the ZnO@N-GQDs@MIP probe (blue line 
                           Fig. S6
                        ). Consequently, the fluorescent quenching phenomenon was not attributed to an energy-transfer mechanism. Instead, it was inferred that the dynamic quenching of fluorescence was due to electron transfer as follows (
                           Fig.S7
                        ). After ZnO@N-GQDs@MIP absorbs UV energy and the conduction band transitions to an excited state, diflunisal interacts with binding sites of ZnO@N-GQDs@MIP. The charge of ZnO@N-GQDs@MIP then transfers from the excited state to the lowest unoccupied molecular orbital (LUMO) of diflunisal, quenching fluorescence [37]. Furthermore, the fluorescence quenching at various concentrations of diflunisal could be described using the Stern–Volmer equation [38]; F0/F = 1 + Ksv[Cdiflunisal], where F0 and F respectively represent fluorescence intensity in the absence and presence of the quencher (diflunisal), Ksv is the Stern-Volmer constant and [Cdiflunisal] represents the concentration of diflunisal.

The zeta potential changes of N-GQDs, and ZnO@N-GQDs@MIP without and with diflunisal were determined (
                           Fig. S8
                        ). The zeta potential of N-GQDs was −34.0 ± 3.5 mV, while the zeta potentials of ZnO@N-GQDs@MIP without and with diflunisal were −32.9 ± 3.7 mV and −23.3 ± 3.3 mV, respectively. The higher zeta potential of N-GQDs was attributed to the presence of nitrogen-containing groups with a tendency to either donate electrons or attract protons, resulting in a more negative charge. The zeta potential of ZnO@N-GQDs@MIP without and with diflunisal indicated the existence of amino groups on the surface of ZnO@N-GQDs@MIP and the interaction between specific binding sites of ZnO@N-GQDs@MIP and diflunisal [39].
